{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596961"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:19:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:19:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15424"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15424"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.19,0.07,0.44,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65932"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8115"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51378"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8761"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22029"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65932"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hepatic lobule is divided into three zones based on oxygen and nutrient gradients from the portal triad to the central vein.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes Zone 3?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contains hepatocytes with highest oxygen tension","First to receive nutrients from portal blood","Located adjacent to the portal triad","Most susceptible to toxic injury","Primary site of gluconeogenesis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EZone 3 (perivenous) hepatocytes are located furthest from the portal triad and closest to the central vein. \u003Cstrong\u003EHighest oxygen tension\u003C/strong\u003E is found in Zone 1 near the portal triad, not Zone 3. Zone 3 is not \u003Cstrong\u003Elocated adjacent to the portal triad\u003C/strong\u003E - this describes Zone 1. \u003Cstrong\u003EGluconeogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E primarily occurs in Zone 1 where oxygen levels are highest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EZone 3 is \u003Cstrong\u003Emost susceptible to toxic injury\u003C/strong\u003E due to high concentrations of cytochrome P450 enzymes and being the last to receive oxygen and nutrients. It is not \u003Cstrong\u003Efirst to receive nutrients from portal blood\u003C/strong\u003E - this occurs in Zone 1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EZone 3 hepatocytes are adapted to their low oxygen environment by primarily performing glycolysis and lipogenesis rather than oxidative metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Zone 3 (perivenous) hepatocytes are located closest to the central vein and have the lowest oxygen tension.","Zone 3 hepatocytes primarily perform lipogenesis and glycolysis due to their low oxygen environment.","Drug-induced liver injury often begins in Zone 3 due to high concentrations of cytochrome P450 enzymes."],"references":["Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kurtovic E, Limaiem F. Mallory Bodies. 2024 Apr 30. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31424884","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51378"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15424"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51378"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T17:32:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T17:32:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8115"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65932"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30